li.p:
Fill in this truth table.
\begin{array}{c|c|c|c} P & Q & P \wedge Q & \neg (P \wedge Q) \\ \hline T & T & & \\ T & F & & \\ F & T & & \\ F & F & & \\ \end{array}
\begin{array}{c|c|c|c} %mathbook tabular P & Q & P \wedge Q & \neg (P \wedge Q) \\ \hline T & T & T& F\\ T & F & F & T\\ F & T & F & T\\ F & F & F & T\\ \end{array}

statement.p:
For x \in \mathbb Z, consider the statements


P(x) = \mbox{"x is even"}  \qquad \qquad
Q(x) = \mbox{"x is positive"}


and let A and B  be the sets


A = \{ x \in \mathbb{Z} \mid P(x) \mbox{ is true} \} \qquad \qquad
B = \{ x \in \mathbb{Z} \mid Q(x) \mbox{ is true} \}


Fill in the blanks using the symbols A, B, \cup and \cap.


\begin{array}{rcl}
\underline{\phantom{asdasdasd}} = \{ x \in \mathbb{Z} \mid P(x) \wedge Q(x)  \mbox{ is true} \} \\
\underline{\phantom{asdasdasd}} = \{ x \in \mathbb{Z} \mid P(x) \vee Q(x)  \mbox{ is true} \}
\end{array}


You have just  turned an expression about mathematical statements into an expression about sets!







\begin{array}{rcl}
A \cap B  = \{ x \in \mathbb{Z} \mid P(x) \wedge Q(x)  \mbox{ is true} \} \\
A \cup B   = \{ x \in \mathbb{Z} \mid P(x) \vee Q(x)  \mbox{ is true} \}
\end{array}
